galaxies, merge and acquire stars to produce a new, transient class of high-redshift objects, obese black hole galaxies (OBGs). The accretion luminosity outshines that of the stars in OBGs. We predict the
multi-wavelength energy output of OBGs and growing Pop III remnants at z = 9 for standard and slim disk accretion, as well as high and low metallicities of the associated stellar population. We derive robust selection criteria for OBGs{\textemdash}a pre-selection to eliminate blue
sources, followed by color{\textendash}color cuts
([\{F\}090W-\{F\}220W]{\textgreater} 0;-0.3{\textless}
[\{F\}200W-\{F\}444W]{\textless} 0.3) and the ratio of X-ray flux to rest-frame optical flux (\{F\}X/\{F\}444W{\textbackslash}gg 1). Our cuts sift out OBGs from other bright, high- and low-redshift contaminants in the infrared. OBGs with predicted \{M\}\{AB\}{\textless} 25 are unambiguously detectable by the Mid-Infrared Instrument (MIRI), on the upcoming James Webb Space Telescope (JWST). For parameters explored here, growing Pop III remnants with predicted
